<h1>5.5 Order of genitive and noun</h1>
<p>DRAFT!</p>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes-syntactic-relation-labels">Relevant postag
codes / syntactic relation labels</h2>
<p><strong>Position in postag string:</strong> 7th (case)</p>
<p><strong>Letters:</strong> g (genitive)</p>
<p><strong>Syntactic label:</strong></p>
<p>The adnominal genitive is annotated with the ATR label (ATR_CO if in
coordination).</p>
<p><strong>Example:</strong></p>
<p>ἀσπαλίσματα <strong>τῆς οἰκίας</strong><br>
aspalísmata tês oikías<br>
<em>security for the house</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/1477">BGU.2.601</a>, 8, sent. 3.</p>
<p></p><div style="height:300px; " data-treeid="1" class="sentence-tree tf-tree tf-result" data-json=""></div><p></p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>In Ancient Greek, including in the variety attested in documentary
papyri, the adnominal genitive can appear before or after its governing
noun. However, in papyri there is a higher preference for the
postposition of the genitive than what is observed in treebanked
literary texts.</p>
<h2 id="discussion">Discussion</h2>
<p>In linguistic typology, a distinction is kept between lexical
genitives, which are nouns, and grammatical genitives, which are
person-marked pronouns or adjectives (<span class="citation" data-cites="koptevskaia2003a">(<strong>koptevskaia2003a?</strong>)</span>).
The discussion below concerns lexical genitives with heads that are
nouns and not proper names.</p>
<p>In addition to pragmatic factors, which cannot be programmatically
queried from the treebanked data, the presence of other modifiers in the
NP, the semantics of the np-head and the genitive, the syntactic
function of the genitive, and its definiteness all influence the
position of the adnominal genitive in the phrase. In our corpus the
assortment of lemmata participating in NPs with adnominal genitives also
affects the distributions.</p>
<h3 id="influence-of-the-presence-of-other-modifiers-in-the-np">Influence of
the presence of other modifiers in the NP</h3>
<p>The presence of another modifier in the NP influences the order
patterns of the genitive. In literary prose, when the np-head is
modified by a genitive plus another modifier (in both articular and
non-articular phrases), the genitive is more often postposed than in
phrases where it is the only modifier. In papyri, however, while this
trend is observable in articular phrases, the opposite can be found in
non-articular phrases - when the genitive is the sole modifier of the
NP, it has predominantly postposed occurrences, while when there is
another modifier in addition to it, it is more often placed before the
noun. The majority of such phrases are modified by a numeral, which is
placed after the noun, while the genitive is extracted to the left of
it:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li><strong>σίτου</strong> ἀρτάβας δύο<br>
sítou artábas dúo<br>
<em>two artabae of grain</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/35065">p.oxy.14.1680</a>, 18, sent.
5.</li>
</ol>
<p>For comparison, in the literary corpus, there is an equal chance for
the genitive to appear before or after the noun, when there is a numeral
present in the noun phrase as the only other modifier.</p>
<p>In order to avoid conflating possible influences to the position of
the genitive, the present discussion only covers NPs which have the
genitive as the sole modifier.</p>
<h3 id="semantics-of-the-np-head-and-the-adnominal-genitive">Semantics
of the np-head and the adnominal genitive</h3>
<p>Previous research suggests that, while topicality and the pragmatic
context are the most influential factor for the position of the genitive
in the NP in literary prose, it is also strongly related to the extended
animacy hierarchy. With decreasing frequency, common nouns of human
beings, animals, inanimate objects, and mass nouns that are not
specified by a numeral appear before their governing noun. <span class="citation" data-cites="viti2008">(Viti 2008, 227)</span>.</p>
<h3 id="syntactic-function-of-the-genitive">Syntactic function of the
genitive</h3>
<p>In Literature, the syntactic function of the genitive is influential
for its position in the NP, as presented in earlier studies on the noun
phrase <span class="citation" data-cites="manolessou2000">(Manolessou
2000)</span> and confirmed by an investigation of the literary
treebanked corpus. When the genitive is argumental (objective or
subjective), the likelihood of it appearing in internal position
(between the article and the np-head) is much higher than if it is
partitive or possessive. In the documentary texts in the PapyGreek
corpus, however, argumental genitives display no such preference, and
tend to be most often postposed:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>περὶ τῆς πράσεως <strong>τῶν ἱματίων</strong><br>
perì tês práseōs tôn himatíōn<br>
<em>for the making of the cloacks</em><br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/27748">p.giss.apoll.16</a>, 2, sent.
2.</li>
</ol>
<h3 id="variety-of-lemmata-participating-in-nps-with-adnominal-genitives">Variety
of lemmata participating in NPs with adnominal genitives</h3>
<p>Due to the size of our corpus and the specificity of topics covered
in documentary texts, there is a smaller assortment of lemmata
participating in NPs with adnominal genitives, both of the np-head and
of the genitive, in comparison to the literary treebank. This higher
repeatability in papyri increases the influence of individual lemmata
and their respective potential preferred order patterns on the overall
corpus results. The 7 most common lemma appearing as np-head governing
an adnominal genitive, whose occurrences as np-heads account for 21%% of
the NPs with adnominal genitives in PapyGreek, have almost exclusively
postposed genitives.</p>
<h3 id="definiteness-of-the-genitive">Definiteness of the genitive</h3>
<p>In Literature, the definiteness of the genitive plays a significant
role for its position in the NP. Non-articular genitives are more often
preposed than postposed, while articular genitives appear more often
after their governing noun.<a href="#fn1" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref1" role="doc-noteref"><sup>1</sup></a> On the contrary, in
papyri there is no notable difference between the preferred placement of
articular and non-articular genitives.<a href="#fn2" class="footnote-ref" id="fnref2" role="doc-noteref"><sup>2</sup></a></p>
<h3 id="syllable-heaviness">Syllable heaviness</h3>
<p>In literary Greek there is an observable preference to put genitives
that are lighter (i.e.&nbsp;have fewer syllables) than their governing noun
before the noun, and those that are heavier - after. This trend is not
discovered in papyri, where lighter genitives are commonly placed after
their head.</p>
